<sn><md>### Viewing Working Directory vs Staging Area Changes{.text-center}

By default, `git diff` shows the difference between the **working directory** (your unsaved file changes) and the **staging area**.

#### Syntax

```bash
git diff
```

#### Example

```bash
$ echo "new line" &gt;&gt; file1.md
$ git diff
diff --git a/file1.md b/file1.md
index e69de29..5f1d7d2 100644
--- a/file1.md
+++ b/file1.md
@@
+new line
```

Here:

* `+new line` indicates that a line has been added.
* &gt; Since the file is not staged yet, this diff ++shows only unstaged changes++.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Viewing Staging Area vs Last Commit Changes

If you want to see what has been staged (via `git add`) but not yet committed, you can use:

#### Syntax

```bash
git diff --cached
```

or

```bash
git diff --staged
```

#### Example

```bash
$ git add file1.md
$ git diff --cached
diff --git a/file1.md b/file1.md
index e69de29..5f1d7d2 100644
--- a/file1.md
+++ b/file1.md
@@
+new line
```

Here:

* The changes shown are the ones already **staged**.
* These will be included in the **next commit**.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Comparing Working Directory + Staging Area Together

To see **all changes since the last commit** (both staged and unstaged):

```bash
git diff HEAD
```

This compares the entire project (working directory + staging area) against the last commit.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Summary of Key Commands

| Command             | Compares                                            |
| ------------------- | --------------------------------------------------- |
| `git diff`          | Working directory ↔ Staging area (unstaged changes) |
| `git diff --cached` | Staging area ↔ Last commit (staged changes)         |
| `git diff HEAD`     | Working directory + Staging area ↔ Last commit      |
